 are plentiful-and grow disheartened by a public conversation that continually casts them as the problem with urban schools.By showing that young people are deeply committed to education but often critical of the kind of education they are receiving, this book highlights the dishonesty of public claims that they do not value education. Ultimately, these powerful student voices remind us of the ways we have shirked our public responsibility to create excellent schools. True school reform requires no less than a new civil rights movement, where adults join with young people to ensure an equal education for each and every student.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aDe facto school segregationzUnited States. 0aEducation, UrbanzUnited States. 0aMinority teenagersxEducationzUnited States. 0aMinority teenagerszUnited StatesxAttitudes. 4aAfrican. 4aAmerican. 4aLatino. 4aOur. 4aSuck. 4aattend. 4acompelling. 4agives. 4ainner-city. 4aschools. 4astories. 4astudents. 4aunder-resourced. 4avoice. 7aEDUCATION / Student Life & Student Affairs.2bisacsh1 aAlonso, Gaston, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aAnderson, Noel S., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNYUP Backlist 2000-2013z978311070644440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814707760423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780814707760.jpg  a978-3-11-070644-4  NYUP Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK